I just have a few things to say..
(These are my personal opinions)

In order to do a proper swab:
- you need to know human anatomy cos the swab can be inserted way too far in or not ‘deep enough’ to get a proper sample & it could cause more harm than good. Physically & emotionally harmful. & imagine if you went through all that & the results turned false negative or false positive due to improper techniques. - abt human anatomy again, all patients have different nasal passage lengths. You can’t just ‘see the swab stick & oh, it should be till about here’ - with regards to infection control practices, oh man.. where do I begin? Key words: prevent cross contamination. From the patient to the swabbed. From the swabbed to patient. From swabber to specimen. Idk if I’m making sense here but my medical friends will understand. 
I could go on but.. all I can say is that, this article has demoralised a few of the medical personnel.

I'd like to think the healthcare sector is already overworked and allowing non-experts to partially reduce the burden is a solution. and I think we need to have a bit of faith that there was due diligence before they decided to let non-experts be swabbers. Also, we're not replacing the experts - after the situation calms down, the experts get to keep their jobs and the volunteers will be asked to leave. I think a more accurate analogy would be: there isn't enough manpower to fight an extremely large fire and so, to get people to help the fire, we had to outsource for the time being. ofc they'd have to pay a high amount to incentivize people to join. @agnyk__ thank you for doing what you're doing. I think we need to realize that there are two issues here that are not necessarily on two ends of a seesaw as what @mrkaushikvyas has explained: 1. Swabbers are being paid a high amount. This in itself isn't exactly an issue because there are risks involved, and more importantly, it's a short term measure to alleviate the stress on the healthcare system. And I think they've identified $3k+ to be the suitable amount to incentive people who don't inherently have the need to serve like our nurses do to help. 2. Nurses are underpaid. Yes, you guys face a lot of risks and for that, you guys should be compensated accordingly. This issue only highlighted that but the way to approach this shouldn't be: reduce the swabbers' allowance but rather, it should be: increase the healthcare workers' pay. Of course, this is ideal and I'm not an economist nor am I a policy-maker so ofc it's easy for me to be behind the screen and say: increase everyone's pay!

@mrkaushikvyas so yeah, they should have explained it the way you have. Not by saying things like "we will pay them higher than for easier and safer jobs" (I think people are angry at this because she's possibly also referring to nurses and healthcare workers)

We get paid $2000+ for diploma graduates, maybe $1800 for ITE Nurses. We have exposure to needle stick like HIV exposed needles. Put ourselves at risk for infections.
